does the POP drying time slow down if it not exposed to air?<EOS> 

its for a craft project.....i want to use it the way u would use icing....<EOS> 

took a bit of searching to discover that POP is probably PoP - plaster of Paris
and yes plaster of Paris will slow way down if it is not exposed to air - in
fact, if you are building up plaster ("the way you would icing") to do
sculpting, which is rather uncommon, you keep the set plaster damp in order to
add more unset plaster or you have to wet the area where you will be adding
plaster "mud"<EOS> Plaster of Paris does two things<EOS> - it chemically sets - gets warm
to hot then cools down and hard and<EOS> - it dries out, losing the water that is
soaked into the set structure<EOS> For example, a set plaster mold that is to be used
for clay slip casting must be dry - it gets wet pulling the water out of the
slip - while a set plaster mold used for molding wax must be soaking or damp wet
http://www.mikegigi.com/castgobl.htm#LGGOBPROJ<EOS> 

